Data Exploration

Kim Pham

5/18/2019

Data exploration and cleaning

  • Download and assess the data
  • Identify and document any issues with the data
  • Document how you resolved these issues

Dataset Description

  • NYC yellow cab data from the months of March, June, and November in 2017.
  • NYC Taxi & Limousine Commission - Trip Record Data
  • Data Dictionary

Load libraries

library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

Upload data csv files

NYC yellow cab data from March, June, and November of 2017

df_mar <- read_csv("data/yellow_tripdata_2017-03.csv")
df_jun <- read_csv("data/yellow_tripdata_2017-06.csv")
df_nov <- read_csv("data/yellow_tripdata_2017-11.csv")

Combine files

df <- bind_rows(df_mar,  df_jun) %>% bind_rows(df_nov)

## #   store_and_fwd_flag <chr>, PULocationID <dbl>, DOLocationID <dbl>,
## #   payment_type <dbl>, fare_amount <dbl>, extra <dbl>, mta_tax <dbl>,
## #   tip_amount <dbl>, tolls_amount <dbl>, improvement_surcharge <dbl>,
## #   total_amount <dbl>
# passenger count 192 has 1 observation; intuitively a taxi ride with 192 passengers does not make sense
# there rides with 0 counts; let's only consider rides where there is at least one or more passengers
df <- filter(df, passenger_count!=192) # remove row where passenger count is 192 from dataset
df <- filter(df, passenger_count>0) # remove rows where passenger count = 0 from dataset
hist(df$passenger_count, labels=TRUE) 

# more often trips have 1 or two passengers; least often trips have more than 6 passengers
